english:
  title: Stele Inscription for Venerable Myogyeom
  author: Byeon Gyeyangn
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the tenth lunar month of the first year of our Great Ancestor's reign, the Master was summoned to the capital of Songgyeong. On the eleventh day of that month, when the Great Ancestor celebrated his birthday, the Master was invested with the highest honors: Royal Preceptor of the Great Jogye School, Supreme Arbiter of Seon and Scriptural Teaching, Transmitter of the Buddha-Mind Seal through Keen Discernment, Upholder of the Unobstructed Path, Architect of the Dharma's Abundant Benefit for Universal Salvation—the Great Master Myogyeom the Venerable One. Assembled there were monks from all the temples of both schools and five teachings.

    Having ascended the seat of the Royal Preceptor, burned incense, and pronounced the benediction, the Master raised his whisk and showed it to the assembly, saying: "This—the three times' Buddhas have never reached it, the ancestral teachers of ages cannot transmit it. Can you multitude truly understand? If you calculate and compare with discriminating mind and tongue, what remains of our Seon lineage?"

    Then addressing the sovereign, he said: "Confucianism speaks of humaneness; Buddhism speaks of compassion. Yet their function is one. When you protect the people as you would an infant, you become their father and mother. When you govern the realm with supreme humaneness and great compassion, naturally the sacred life knows no bound, the golden branches flourish eternal, and the nation's welfare endures. Now at the founding's beginning, many have fallen into criminal punishment. I humbly pray that Your Majesty regard all with equal compassion and grant amnesty to all, that ministers and people alike may enter the realm of humaneness and longevity. This is our nation's boundless blessing."

    The sovereign heard and greatly approved, immediately releasing prisoners throughout the realm and provinces. At that time, the Retired Scholar Lee Munsong of Hansansan composed a poem for the Master:

    "The sagely lord rides the dragon toward heaven,
    The royal preceptor: the Buddha emerging into the world."

    The sovereign commanded the Master to enter the great hall where the lazy master Nong lived at Hoegyeamsa Temple. In the autumn of Jeongchuk year, the sovereign ordered a longevity stupa erected on the northern cliff, where his late master Jigong's reliquary rested. In the autumn of Muin year, the Master, having grown old, resigned and returned to dwell at Yongmun. In the fifth lunar month of Imowon year, our present sovereign commanded the Master again to enter Hoegyeamsa. The following January, he again retired to reside in Geumgangsan, where he entered nirvana on the eleventh day of the ninth lunar month of Eulyu year.

    Three years later, in the twelfth lunar month of Jeonghai year, the sovereign commanded Prince Uian and Minister Hwa to inter the Master's remains in the stupa at Hoegyeam. Four years hence, in the seventh lunar month of autumn, he was posthumously given a name. The former king expressed the Great Ancestor's wishes to the current sovereign, who commanded this subject Gyeyangn to name the stupa and compose this inscription.

    This subject humbly examined the biography compiled by the Master's disciple Jorum: The Master's personal name was Jachao, his dharma name Muhak. He dwelt in the Hermitage of Moonlit Valley. He lived seventy-nine years, with sixty-one years in the religious life. He was of the Park clan from Samgi County. His father, Inil, received the posthumous title of Minister of State. His mother was Lady Chae of Goseong. She dreamed of the morning sun entering her bosom and became pregnant, giving birth to the Master on the twentieth day of the ninth lunar month of Taejung Jeongmyo year.

    Scarcely weaned, he spontaneously began sweeping. When he took to learning, none dared surpass him. At eighteen, he suddenly felt the impulse to transcend the world. He received the tonsure and full precepts from Master Soji, the senior disciple of National Master Hyegam. Coming to Yongmun Mountain, he inquired into the dharma with National Masters Hyemyeong and Bopjang. When their teaching was complete, they said: "Who but you could comprehend the straight path?" They installed him in the Reliquary Hermitage.

    One day fire broke out in the hermitage. The Master sat alone unmoved, like a wooden statue. The assembly marveled. In the autumn of Byeongseul year, while contemplating the Surangama Sutra, he attained awakening. Returning, he informed his master, who exclaimed in praise. From then on, forgetting sleep and neglecting sustenance, he devoted himself entirely to practice.

    In the autumn of Gichuk year, he came to Gilsangsa in Jinju and dwelt there. In the summer of Imjin year, he resided in the Diamond Grotto of Myohyangsan, his practice advancing greatly. Sometimes in sleep, as if someone struck a bell or stone chime to wake him, he would suddenly awaken. His yearning to find a master grew urgent.

    In the autumn of Gyesa year, he journeyed to Yanjing to pay respects to the Western master Jigong. Upon rising from his prostrations he said: "Having traveled three thousand eight hundred li, I have beheld the face of the master." Jigong replied: "I shall slay all Koreans"—meaning approval. The assembly was astounded.

    In the first lunar month of the following Gapgo year, he arrived at Bopcheonsa and paid respects to the Lazy Master. The Lazy Master, seeing him once, recognized a superior vessel. After wandering through Muryeong and crossing Odaesan, he met the Lazy Master again at Seosan Yeongamsa Temple and remained for some years.

    During his meditative absorption, he would sometimes not notice mealtime. The Lazy Master, observing this, remarked: "Have you died?" The Master merely smiled without answer.

    One day, sitting on the steps with the Master, the Lazy Master asked: "Once, Master Jojoo and the head monk examined a stone bridge. Jojoo asked, 'Who built this?' The head monk answered, 'Lee Ung built it.' Jojoo asked, 'Where did he first set his hand?' The head monk could not respond. Now, if someone asks you this, how would you answer?" The Master immediately grasped the step-stone with both hands and demonstrated. The Lazy Master simply departed.

    That night, the Master came to the Lazy Master's room. The master said: "Only today do I know I have not deceived you." Later he told the Master: "Though one may be recognized throughout heaven and earth, how many truly understand one's heart? You and I have become one family. The Way, when in a person, is like ivory in an elephant—though one wishes to hide it, it cannot be concealed. In time, will you not stand as a beacon before others?"

    The Master's attainment was beyond doubt. Yet his aspiration to wander mountains and visit teachers remained unquenched. He wished to travel through Jiangsu and Zhejiang, but as the south was in turmoil, the roads were blocked, so he ceased his plans.

    In the summer of Byeongsin year, desiring to return home, he took his leave. The Lazy Master personally wrote a letter of farewell:

    "In his daily conduct, the entire function differs from the world's. He neither thinks of good and evil, sage and profane, nor heeds human sentiment and righteousness. When utterance and breath emerge, arrow-points oppose each other. When meaning aligns with function, water returns to water. In one gulp, both guest and host phrases are swallowed; through the Buddha-Patriarch's gate, the body passes entirely. Now abruptly departing, I send this verse:

    Already believing another heaven exists within your satchel,
    East and west, leave the three mysteries to work freely.
    If someone asks your meaning in the pilgrimage,
    Strike down the front gate—speak not another word."

    When the Master returned, the Lazy Master came back bearing Jigong's prophecy of the Three Mountains and Two Waters, dwelling at Wongyoam on Cheongseongsan. In the summer of Gihai year, the Master visited and received the whisk. The Lazy Master was at Singwangsa; the Master also stayed there. Some among the Lazy Master's followers were jealous, but the Master, knowing this, departed.

    The Lazy Master told him: "In transmitting the dharma, robe and bowl pale beside word and phrase." He gave a poem:

    "Idle monks stir the mind of self and other,
    Falsely speaking right and wrong—not right at all.
    The mountain priest, with this four-line verse,
    Cuts off all future doubts forever.

    In parting the robe's hem lies special deliberation—
    Who knows the meaning within grows ever profound?
    Though all you people call it impossible,
    My words pierce the kalpa-void completely."

    The Master entered the Hermitage of Gogdalsan. In the winter of Sinha year, the former sovereign Kongmin invested the Lazy Master as Royal Preceptor, and the Lazy Master, dwelling at Songgwangsa, transmitted his robe and bowl to the Master. The Master responded with a verse of gratitude.

    In the summer of Byeongfin year, the Lazy Master moved to Hoegyamsa and held a grand consecration assembly, urgently summoning the Master to serve as head monk. The Master respectfully declined. The Lazy Master said: "Much administration is not better than much retirement. Even Deshan and Linji did not serve as head monks; coming here, simply remain in the hermitage." When the Lazy Master passed, the Master wandered mountains, hiding his traces, revealing himself to none.

    In the late period of the former dynasty, though officials summoned him with honors and sought to appoint him Royal Preceptor, the Master never came. At last, in Imsin year—the first year of our Great Ancestor—the Master's encounter was fated. Was this mere chance?

    In Gyeyou year, the Great Ancestor wished to establish a new capital and commanded the Master to accompany the court. The Master declined, but the Great Ancestor said: "Meeting now or in ages past occurs through karma. Can the world's geomancer match the master's eye?" The Master attended the inspection of Gyeryongsan and the new capital.

    That September, by royal decree, the Master engraved the names of his two former masters' stupas—Jigong and the Lazy Master—at Hoegyamsa, and held a grand assembly to display the Lazy Master's portrait at Gwangmyeongsa. He composed a eulogy for his master's image:

    "Jigong's thousand swords and Pyeongsan's sharp reproof,
    Functioning through practice, proclaimed before the throne.
    His final radiance left crystalline relics—
    The patriarchal seat of Three Han shall transmit them ten thousand ages."

    In the tenth lunar month, the nation held a sutra-recitation assembly at Yeonboksa and appointed the Master as presiding abbot. Yet since his resignation in Muin year, the Master had grown weary of public attendance. Though the royal command came, he withdrew to Hoegyeamsa, then entered Geumgangsan to dwell in the True Buddha Hermitage.

    In the spring of Eulyu year, he fell slightly ill. His attendant wished to offer medicine, but the Master declined, saying: "At eighty years with sickness, what use is medicine?" In the fourth lunar month of summer, he moved to the Diamond Treasury Hermitage—the place of his final nirvana. In the eighth lunar month, Prince Uian sent a letter. The Master's reply contained: "My mountain dwelling is distant; opportunity to meet is uncertain. Perhaps in some future Buddha-assembly we shall encounter."

    He told the assembly: "Soon I shall depart." And so it came to pass. As his illness grew critical, a monk asked: "When the four elements each separate, where do they go?" The Master answered: "I don't know." Asked again, he replied sharply: "I don't know." Another monk asked: "In the master's sickness, is there that which is not sick?" The Master pointed with his finger at a nearby monk. Asked: "The body of form is earth, water, fire, wind—which is the true dharma-body?" The Master, crossing his arms, said: "This is one."

    Having answered, he quietly passed away—at midnight.

    At that time, the Huayan monk Changi, dwelling at Beopwangsa in Songgyeong, dreamed he saw the Master standing upon a lotus flower at the Buddha's crown in empty space, the Buddha and lotus vast as the heavens. Upon waking, he marveled and shared the dream with the temple assembly. All who heard doubted it was no ordinary dream. Within days, news arrived: the Master had entered nirvana at precisely the hour of the dream.

    The Master's work, the "Printing-Void Singing," was prefaced by Minister Lee and later published in the Great Canon, enshrined at Yongmunsa, with Minister Lee providing the colophon.

    The Master's nature abhorred ornamentation; his self-support was spare, and surplus he gave in charity. He often said: "Among the eighty thousand practices, the infant's way is supreme." All his deeds matched this standard. His reception of others was reverent, his love for creatures sincere—emanating from genuine heart, not forced effort. Truly this was his nature.

    This subject humbly bows and names the stupa: "Compassion-Wisdom's Vast Convergence," and hereby composes this inscription:

    Lofty stood the Master's way—
    Not the common mind's measure.
    The true lineage of awakening,
    The Great Ancestor's guide.

    The Master in daily life:
    Infant-like,
    Meeting the keen-eyed,
    Arrow-tips opposing each other.

    One robe, one bowl,
    Humble, ever humble, lowering himself.
    The realm's veneration found no peer,
    Yet he remained cautious as ever.

    Going forth or withdrawing,
    Never schemes or grasping.
    Heaven granted his span:
    Seventy-nine years—

    Whence came he?
    The rising sun embraced in the womb.
    Whither went he?
    The lotus in heaven above.

    His devoted followers
    Planned to honor his traces.
    Between heaven and earth,
    Nothing outlasts the stone.

    Upon this monument the words are carved,
    Shown to ages without end.
  footnotes:
    - 'The Four Elements (地水火風): According to Buddhist philosophy, the fundamental constituents composing the physical body. Their separation at death represents the dissolution of material form.'
    - 'Jigong (指空) and the Lazy Master (懶翁): Two influential Seon masters of the Goryeo period; Jigong was the predecessor of the Lazy Master and both were venerated teachers within the Seon lineage.'
